o achieving victory in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Gawthorpe tells a story of policy aspirations and practical failures that stretches from Washington, DC, to the Vietnamese villages in which the US implemented its nation-building strategy. Structural factors which could not have been overcome by the further application of military power thwarted U.S. efforts to build a viable set of non-communist political, economic, and social institutions in South Vietnam.To Build as Well as Destroy provides the most comprehensive account yet of the largest and best-resourced nation-building program in U.S. history. Gawthorpe's analysis helps contemporary policy makers, diplomats, and military officers understand the reasons for this failure. At a moment in time when American strategists are grappling with military and political challenges in Afghanistan, Iraq, and Syria, revisiting the historical lessons of Vietnam is a worthy endeavor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aNation-buildingzVietnam (Republic) 0aNation-buildingzVietnam (Republic). 4aMilitary History. 4aU.S. History. 4aVietnam. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aVietnam War, unseen oral histories, failure of U.S to achieve victory, Washington, non-Communist state in South Vietnam.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501709456?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709456zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709456/original  a978-3-11-060655-3 Cornell University Pres